. Lady Hamilton was so obviously lacking in the subservience and passivity expected from women in that era that authors started to exclude her public sphere of influence by reducing her to a private weakness of Nelson's, who could be successful at sea, where he was far away from the enthralling influence of a manipulating woman. The letters in this edition testify how Admiral Nelson's life at sea was not exclusively public nor was Lady Hamilton's life ashore solely private. It also shows how the two supposedly separate spheres of male and female lives were connected. This scholarly edition of the primary material consists of about 400 letters that Nelson wrote to Lady Hamilton during the last seven years of his life and about a dozen letters of her to him that have survived.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAdmiralsvCorrespondencezGreat Britain. 0aAdmiralszGreat BritainvCorrespondence. 4aMaritime History. 7aHISTORY / Military / Napoleonic Wars .2bisacsh  a, Charles Connor.  a4th Duke of Queensbury.  aAdmiralty.  aAlexander Davison.  aBaltic.  aBattle of Cape St Vincent.  aBattle of Copenhagen.  aBattle of the Nile.  aEarl St Vincent.  aFrench Revolutionary War.  aGibraltar.  aHMS St George.  aHMS Victory.  aHoratia Nelson.  aKing of Naples.  aLady Hamilton.  aLord Nelson.  aLord William Gordon.  aMalta, Mary Cadogan.  aMediterranean.  aNapoleon Bonaparte.  aQueen of Naples.  aRoyal Navy.  aSarah Nelson.  aSir William Hamilton.  aThomas Hardy.  aThomas Troubridge.  aWest Indies.  aWilliam Nelson.  athe Later Georian Navy.  athe Napoleonc Wars.1 aCzisnik, Marianne R.E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://w